suffering and sorrow Japan inflicted" by its "reckless" decision 50 years ago
this week to start a war with the United States.;   In an interview, Foreign
Minister Michio Watanabe said the Japanese government "isn't seeking any kind
of apology" from the United States for the atomic-bomb blasts at Hiroshima and
Nagasaki that brought the war to an end in 1945. President Bush said Sunday
the United States would not apologize for using the bombs.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  JAPAN EXPRESSES REMORSE FOR WAR  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Though he did not make a specific apology for Japan's role in World War II,
Watanabe immediately launched into a long condemnation of the Japanese actions
that led to the war.;   Watanabe also pledged that the national parliament
would "definitely" pass a formal resolution expressing regret to the people of
the United States and other countries Japan fought in the war. "This is a
milestone," he said.  </TEXT>
